TY  - JOUR
T1  - Transshipment and Its Impact on Supply Chain Members’ Performance
AU  - Zhang, Jun
Y1  - 2005/10/01
PY  - 2005
DA  - 2005/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.1050.0397
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.1050.0397
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 1534
EP  - 1539
VL  - 51
IS  - 10
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - This note extends some of the key results of Dong and Rudi (2004) to general demand distributions. This generalization is achieved in two steps. First, we build on the analysis of Dong and Rudi to demonstrate that an inventory problem with transshipment is equivalent to a newsvendor problem with an adjusted demand. Then, we study the impact of transshipment by comparing the adjusted demand with the original demand. In addition to extending the results in the existing literature, this note presents a novel approach for analyzing the impact of risk pooling.
AB  - This note extends some of the key results of Dong and Rudi (2004) to general demand distributions. This generalization is achieved in two steps. First, we build on the analysis of Dong and Rudi to demonstrate that an inventory problem with transshipment is equivalent to a newsvendor problem with an adjusted demand. Then, we study the impact of transshipment by comparing the adjusted demand with the original demand. In addition to extending the results in the existing literature, this note presents a novel approach for analyzing the impact of risk pooling.
